\quote{
\poem{
\line{Glory be to thee, O Lord, glory be to thee,}
\line{Creator of the visible light, }
\line{the sun’s ray, the flame of fire;}
\line{Creator also of the light invisible and} \line{intellectual:}
\line{that which is known of God, the light invisible.} 
\line{Glory be to thee, O Lord, glory be to thee,}
\line{Creator of the light.}
\line{for writings of the law, glory be to thee:}
\line{for oracles of prophets, glory be to thee:}
\line{for melody of psalms, glory be to thee:}
\line{for wisdom of proverbs, glory be to thee:}
\line{experience of histories, glory be to thee:}
\line{a light which never sets.}
\line{God is the Lord, who hath shewed us light.\br}
\line{Light, who dost my soul enlighten;}
\line{Sun, who all my life dost brighten;}
\line{Joy, the sweetest man e’er knoweth;}
\line{Fount, whence all my being floweth.}
\line{From thy banquet let me measure,}
\line{Lord, how vast and deep its treasure;}
\line{Through the gifts thou here dost give us,}
\line{As thy guest in heaven receive us.  }
  }
}
  \p{As usual we did John Kitchen's [Divine Praises](https://youtu.be/Iuxew7FwMpc?t=3440) at the end during the Benediction, which was a magical experience when I first heard it in the congregation of OSP years ago.}
  
